<h1>Explore Small Examples:  Find a Pattern</h1>

<p>
This is the first thing I try when I get stuck.  The idea is a simple one:

<ol>
  <li>Start with the smallest version of the question you can.</li>
  <li>Then make it "1 larger".</li>
  <li>Keep going and organize your results in a table.</li>
  <li>Try to find a pattern you can use.</li>
</ol>

Some examples should make this clearer.
</p>

<h3>Examples:  How to start</h3>

<p><b>Problem 1:  Cutting a pancake</b>
What's the maximum number of pieces you can cut a pancake into with 10 straight cuts?
</p>
<p>This is hard to experiment with.  If you draw 10 lines, it's hard even to count the pieces.  And how in the world can you know if you could get more pieces?
</p>
<p>SO:  Explore small cases!  How many pieces can you get with just 1 cut?  That's easy.  How many pieces can you get with 2 cuts?  Also easy.  3 cuts?  It helps to organize your experiments in a table.  See any patterns that might help you with the original problem?
</p>
<p>(Note:  This is great for beginning problem solvers.  The next step is understanding why the pattern is really there, and proving that it will continue.  To see this next step, look at our tutorial on **link**).
</p>

<p><b>Problem 2:  Game on a circular table.</b>
You have a circular table.  You and a partner will take turns putting pennies flat on the table.  You can't overlap another penny, and you can't hang your penny off the edge of the table.  The first player who can't put a penny down because there's not enough room looses.  Explain how the 1st player can always win.
</p>
<p>
This problem is different because there aren't any numbers!  The answer is also not a number, but a strategy.  How can you start?  How big is the table?  It sounds like the strategy should work on tables of any size.
</p>
<p>So:  Explore small examples!  Start with the smallest table you possibly can.  How small is that?  Well, it needs to be at least the width of a penny for anyone to play at all, so let's start with that table.  Obviously, the 1st player will always win because there's only room for one penny.
</p>
<p>So, let's make the table "1 bigger".  What's that?  Well, how about making a circular table that's as wide as 2 pennies.
</p>
<p>So, let's make the table "1 bigger".  Let's look at a table that's 3 pennies wide.
</p>

